title: For Sale:  Engraved BSA Lee-Speed British Officer's Carbine Rare Metford LEC LE I Sporting Enfield Rifle .303
postcontent: Please read the Additional Terms of Sale and Item Characteristics for important listing details.PENNY START, TWELVE DAY, NO RESERVE AUCTIONLee-Speed Officer's Carbine; ca.1899 BSA, Birmingham, England Production; .303 British; Barrel: 24 1/2"Rare, Boer-War era Lee-Speed Officer's Private Purchase Carbine...this short rifle was manufactured by legendary Birminham maker BSA in ca.1899 and subsequently retailed, most likely in an Army & Navy store, for sale to a British Officer preparing to embark on campaign. An unusually styled example, the gun has been finished with rarely-seen border engraving, fitted with Grade-A, flamed English Walnut furniture that has been capped with an engraved metal buttplate, capped with a silver monogram shield escutcheon, and painstakingly hand-checkered. Chambered in the military-standard .303 British, these weapons were marketed to officers who were, at the time, expected to furnish their own service arms. For most, this meant the simple acquisition of a handgun, but officers in the cavalry, as well as others with duties requiring a shoulder arm, tended to favor the Metford-rifled Lee-Speed carbine, which was an ideal choice for both combat, and hunting exotic game in locales that may have included India, Africa and the Middle East. As such, the Lee-Speed was really a dual-usage rifle, serving as both a martial and sporting arm. Rarely encountered by collectors on the North American market, this Boer War-era Lee-Speed carbine would be an outstanding addition to any advanced Victorian or Colonial arms collection.Condition:Very fine with the gun showing no evidence of refinish. Metal surfaces retain better than 85% bluing overall, with old grease, carbon spotting, and a dash or two of light surface pitting, but no deep pitting or rust present. The bulk of finish loss is in the form of high edge wear and flaking along the dust cover. Markings are correct, well struck and, apart from the service-replacement, 10-round magazine, the gun appears composed of original, matching components, with the only apparent serial number being on the buttstock(the number on the bolt handle is a retailer register number). Engraving is nicely executed vine/scroll that rims the border of nearly the entire receiver, and extends to the dust cover, pistol grip cap, and buttplate. The furniture rates as fine in line with the gun, displaying pressure dents, handling marks, dings and wear to the checkering, but no cracks, chips or repairs. Mechanically excellent, with smooth, fluid action, the bore rates as good with strong, evident Metford rifling as well as light wear and moderate frost running the length. A post-1968 export from the UK, the importer mark is discretely placed under the barrel(pictured). Original Magazine Cutoff is in place.
